result.execSummary:
The defendant Catherine Sue Gallitz was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Catherine Sue Gallitz is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Catherine Sue Gallitz was found guilty of Burglary-Building or Dwelling [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.10(1m)(a).
  • Catherine Sue Gallitz was found guilty of Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).
  • Catherine Sue Gallitz was found guilty of Criminal Damage to Property [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.01(1).
  • Catherine Sue Gallitz was found guilty of Theft-Movable Property <=$2500 [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(a).

records.addlTxt: Defendant Catherine Sue Gallitz appeared by video, in custody at Jefferson County Jail.  Attorney Anthony Joseph Pozorski Sr. in court for State of Wisconsin.  Attorney Peter A. Bartelt in court for Catherine Sue Gallitz. Per agreement, defendant will plea to Cts 1, 2, 3, and 5. State will move to dismiss Cts 4 and 6. State will recommend defendant to pay restitution, advise court of prior record but remain silent as to sentencing. Defendant is okay will appearing via zoom for sentencing. Court reviews plea questionnaire and finds defendant freely and knowingly waives rights. Defendant pleads no contest to Cts 1, 2, 3, and 5. Court accepts plea and finds defendant guilty of Cts 1, 2, 3, and 5. Court dismisses Cts 4 and 6 per agreement. State heard on restitution and prior record. Attorney Bartelt heard. Defendant heard. Court heard and orders 3 years prison (18 months in and 18 months out) for Cts 1 and 2, is eligible for substance abuse and challenges, and 9 months jail for Cts 3 and 5 . All counts are concurrent to each other and concurrent to current sentence. Conditions of extended supervision are: to pay restitution, submit to random observed drug testing, and participate in counseling deemed appropriate by DOC. Court waives court costs on all counts.
